    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="preparation">
Reply to John Bailar</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="17" relname="span">

Speaking for myself, I would strongly resist any attempt to settle on the
goals or essence of STS. </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="justify"> Maybe I&apos;ve sat on too many committees trying to
define a common core of the humanities, the goals of our department, or
whatever, and have some sense of what that&apos;s like. </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="5" relname="solutionhood"> Do medical professors
waste their time in this way? </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="13" relname="span"> I think not.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="14" relname="span">

Also, I suspect that many on this list would find the very exercise of 
defining goals and essences and common cores to be an inerently conser-
vative enterprise. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration"> Scholars like Bloom come to mind.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="circumstance">

As you are a biostastician,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="15" relname="span"> I don&apos;t think I need to lecture you on the 
importance of variation. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="18" relname="span"> Variation makes evolution possible. </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="12" relname="condition"> Settle
on common goals,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="16" relname="span"> and that might just spell the end of things.</segment>
